# Component Model

Document Status: Draft
Document Type: Component Architecture
Template Version: 1.0

---

# 1 Overview

This document defines the component architecture
of the repository system.

The component model identifies the internal
building blocks of the system and defines
their responsibilities, interfaces, and
relationships.

---

# 2 Architectural Components

The system is composed of multiple architectural
components.

Each component represents a logical unit
responsible for a specific capability within
the system.

Typical component types include:

• processing components
• coordination components
• storage components
• interface components

---

# 3 Component Definitions

Each component must be clearly defined.

For each component specify:

Component Name
Component Purpose
Responsibilities
External Interfaces
Dependencies

---

# 4 Component Responsibilities

Define the responsibilities of each component.

Responsibilities should include:

• core functionality
• data processing responsibilities
• coordination logic
• system integration roles

Responsibilities should not overlap between
components.

---

# 5 Component Interfaces

Describe how components interact with each other.

Interface definitions should include:

• method or API definitions
• event contracts
• data exchange formats

Interfaces must remain stable to ensure
system reliability.

---

# 6 Component Dependencies

Describe dependencies between components.

Dependencies should remain aligned with
the Prospera system dependency map.

Circular dependencies must be avoided.

---

# 7 Component Lifecycle

Describe the lifecycle of each component.

Include:

• initialization behaviour
• runtime execution
• shutdown procedures

Lifecycle management ensures predictable
system behaviour.

---

# 8 Fault Isolation

Describe how faults are isolated between
components.

Fault isolation mechanisms may include:

• error boundaries
• retry strategies
• fallback logic

---

# 9 Extensibility

Describe how the component architecture
supports future system evolution.

Include:

• extension points
• plugin architecture
• modular component replacement

